===Verb===
{{en-verb|knits|knitting|knit|past2=knitted}}

# {{lb|en|ambitransitive}} To turn [[thread]] or [[yarn]] into a piece of [[fabric]] by forming loops that are pulled through each other. This can be done by hand with [[needle]]s or by machine.
#: ''to '''knit''' a stocking''
#: ''The first generation '''knitted''' to order; the second still '''knits''' for its own use; the next leaves '''knitting''' to industrial manufacturers.''
# {{lb|en|figuratively|transitive}} To [[join]] closely and firmly together.
#: ''The fight for survival '''knitted''' the men closely together.''
#* '''1609''', {{w|William Shakespeare}}, {{w|Shakespeare's sonnets|Sonnet}} 26,<sup>[http://www.opensourceshakespeare.org/views/sonnets/sonnet_view.php?Sonnet=26]</sup>
#*: Lord of my love, to whom in vassalage
#*: Thy merit hath my duty strongly '''knit''',
#*: To thee I send this written embassage,
#* '''1611''', ''{{w|King James Version}} of the {{w|Bible}}'', {{w|Books of Samuel|1 Samuel}} 18:1,<sup>[https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=1%20Samuel+18&version=KJV]</sup>
#*: And it came to pass, when he had made an end of speaking unto Saul, that the soul of Jonathan was '''knit''' with the soul of David, and Jonathan loved him as his own soul.
#* '''1637''', {{w|John Milton}}, ''{{w|Comus (Milton)|A Maske Presented at Ludlow Castle, 1634}}'', London: Humphrey Robinson, p. 6,<sup>[http://name.umdl.umich.edu/A07555.0001.001]</sup>
#*: Come, '''knit''' hands, and beate the ground
#*: In a light fantastick round.
#* '''1672''', Richard Wiseman, ''A Treatise of Wounds'', London: Richard Royston,<sup>[http://name.umdl.umich.edu/A66731.0001.001]</sup>
#*: Nature cannot '''knit''' the bones while the parts are under a discharge.
#* '''1850''', {{w|Alfred, Lord Tennyson}}, ''{{w|In Memoriam A.H.H.|In Memoriam}}'', London: Edward Moxon, Canto 39, p. 60,<sup>[https://archive.org/details/inmemoriam00tennrich]</sup>
#*: Her office there to rear, to teach,
#*: Becoming as is meet and fit
#*: A link among the days, to '''knit'''
#*: The generations each with each;
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To become closely and firmly joined; become [[compact]]ed.
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[grow]] together.
#: ''All those seedlings '''knitted''' into a kaleidoscopic border.''
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[combine]] from various elements.
#: ''The witness '''knitted''' together his testimony from contradictory pieces of hearsay.''
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} Of bones: to heal following a [[fracture]].
#: I’ll go skiing again after my bones '''knit'''.''
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To form into a [[knot]], or into knots; to tie together, as cord; to fasten by tying.
#* c. '''1596''', {{w|William Shakespeare}}, ''{{w|King John (play)|King John}}'', Act IV, Scene 1,<sup>[http://www.opensourceshakespeare.org/views/plays/play_view.php?WorkID=kingjohn&Scope=entire&pleasewait=1&msg=pl]</sup>
#*: When your head did but ache,
#*: I '''knit''' my handkercher about your brows,
#* '''1611''', ''{{w|King James Version}} of the {{w|Bible}}'', {{w|Book of Acts}} 10:11,<sup>[https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Acts+10&version=KJV]</sup>
#*: [He] saw heaven opened, and a certain vessel descending upon him, as it had been a great sheet '''knit''' at the four corners {{...}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To draw together; to contract into wrinkles.
#* c. '''1590''', {{w|William Shakespeare}}, ''{{w|Henry VI, Part 2}}'', Act III, Scene 1,<sup>[http://www.opensourceshakespeare.org/views/plays/play_view.php?WorkID=henry6p2&Scope=entire&pleasewait=1&msg=pl]</sup>
#*: He '''knits''' his brow and shows an angry eye,

